=C2=A0 https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/michael-byrnes/bounty/


KIRKUS REVIEW
Vigilantism goes viral in this thriller about a website that pays bounties =
for the killing of unpunished child abusers, financial scammers, human righ=
ts violators, and other bad actors.
These are individuals such as Chase Lombardi, a Bernie Madoff=E2=80=93like =
investment banker, who days after his acquittal gets shot through the eye b=
y a sniper in the name of "social justice" while gazing out the window of h=
is posh Manhattan office. The price on his head, as he was informed in taun=
ting text and email alerts: $530,000. More than 20 other people have been t=
argeted by bounty4justice.com in the United States, Europe, and Asia. But e=
ven the savviest techs can't locate the host servers of the site, especiall=
y after it starts dealing in untraceable NcryptoCash. As brutal as the kill=
ings are=E2=80=94a bigoted white congressman is torched in his car by his H=
ispanic limo driver for cancelling insurance benefits, resulting in the dea=
th of the driver's asthmatic son=E2=80=94the people behind bounty4justice a=
re hailed as "freedom fighters" =C3=A0 la Edward Snowden. Soon enough, the =
"proof of death" videos required by the site for payment go viral, a realit=
y show=E2=80=93like fever grips the nation, and ordinary citizens are compe=
ting with professional assassins for prize money. Byrnes (The Genesis Plagu=
e, 2010, etc.) has a solid, if far-fetched, premise to work with, and he kn=
ows his way around secure message boards and such. But he spends so much ti=
me cataloging the assorted targets and the workings of the site that he ris=
ks wearing the reader out. And the book never delivers the kind of dramatic=
 payoff its "cyber spring" promises.
Charles Bronson's=C2=A0Death Watch=C2=A0meets the Internet, with little of =
the hand-wringing melodrama that might suggest.
